g</i> ‘long’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, such as Langford (Bedfordshire, Nottinghamshire, Essex, Norfolk)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lankford","meanings":["English: apparently a variant of   Langford  ."]},{"name":"Langfitt","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Langford  ."]},{"name":"Lanford","meanings":["English: variant of   Langford  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Langford was born in 1390, in Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Elizabeth Wickham about 1415, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 23 June 1419, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1390–23 June 1419":"1390–23. juuni 1419","1398–Female":"1398–Surnud","1416–1474":"1416–1474","1390–1419":"1390–1419","about 1415":"umbes 1415","20 September 1416":"20. september 1416","1398":"1398","1474":"1474","23 June 1419":"23. juuni 1419","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","1416":"1416","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Elvaston Churchyard, Elvaston cum Thurlston